Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1 Verified+1

Deferring the concept of propagating LogdBufferElement::log status until after the klogd adjustment where this problem becomes more serious. Also, this is an _experimental_ idea of enforcing __android_log_is_loggable on _all_ applications; inert for now, but the policy could change to consider DEBUG the default rather than VERBOSE. Thus pending approval of this concept.

Patch Set 13: Code-Review+1 Verified+1

Added `internal' sources of log messages (auditd and logd expire messages) as filterable with __android_log_is_loggable. Doing so because smithd logspam was actually selinux violations, and some folks feel logd expire messages are logspam.

Patch Set 15: Code-Review+1 Verified+1

_this_ is the blacklist mechanism, that will allow us to suppress specific tags from logging. The _next_ patch is a companion and is required to make sure that there is minimal impact (72ns on repeating tags, 400ns on new ones) of less than 1/2 a syscall. All the cycles taken will be at BATCH priority so should defer the impact from the caller(s).

Do you have a test case that demonstrates the problem?

Patch Set 1:

test case is simple.
play music > Pause > observe the condition of the control block. (don't resume)
Unfortunately, the reproducibility is very poor.
This deadlock issue is rarely reproduced in automated stability test.


So, I temporarily added short sleeping time around line 214 to increase reproducibility.
(line 214: int32_t old = android_atomic_and(~CBLK_FUTEX_WAKE, &cblk->mFutex); )

1. While the thread is activated between line 115 (after checking CBLK_INTERRUPT) and line 220 (before syscall) of AudioTrackShared.cpp

2. the thread has been interrupted by pause()

3. then a deadlock has occurred.

Patch Set 1:

>So, I temporarily added short sleeping time around line 214 to increase reproducibility. (line 214: int32_t old = android_atomic_and(~CBLK_FUTEX_WAKE, &cblk->mFutex); )

I would like to try what you are saying,
but I need a little more information.

To make the bug happen more often,
do you add a sleep before or after this line?

And then is there anything else you have to do,
in order to make the bug happen (besides call pause) ?

Patch Set 1:

> do you add a sleep before or after this line?
Both before and after line 214.
I have jest tested on Nexus5 L after insert usleep(500*1000) between line 215 and 216.
ANR didn't occur on Nexus5, but the control block is at a deadlock.
Paly/Pause/Prev/Next does not work because ~AudioTrack() was not completed.

> And then is there anything else you have to do,
  in order to make the bug happen (besides call pause) ?
There is no complex pre-condition but all kind of pause.
play music > pause > observe the condition of the control block.
Please, don't press resume button right after pause() is executed.

Changing to an actual symbol (like for NdkMediaFormat) won't work for the current Android 5.0 out there, so that would only be for the next platform release (and would add antother ABI difference to keep track of, for users).

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

That's only an issue when building against an updated AOSP version of the NDK, and then attempting to run on 5.0 though.
Binaries built against the 5.0 version of the NDK will continue to work, because they have these strings compiled into them.

I agree it's probably easier to just make these #defines though, so let's just do that for now. We can always consider renaming or restructuring later.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

Inserting a delay when changing the audio route is a critical functionality.
We need to find another solution.

Patch Set 2:

This means you make to change from non-blocking to blocking for changing to audio route with delay. I think this causes unpredictable timing or deadlock issues. Anyway, we need to verify this for a while.

Patch Set 2:

What kind of deadlock do you have in mind. Can you be more specific?
There should not be timing issues. The immediate return is more needed for delayed volume commands than routing commands.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I agree with you. Simply I assume that there are 2 routing commend. One have delay and the other have no delay. Originally, 2 routing commend are processed in order of delay. But, After applying this, these will be processed in order of FIFO. Overall, routing commend without delay will be blocked for a while. Of course, this is my own concern theoretically and no hard data. Plus, this is better solution than me. Therefore I will try to test for a couple of days and report if something happens.

Yes, I figured given your address, and since you control the whole OS stack for Firefox OS, I'll only mildly warn you that (as you can clearly tell) the native client-side interface here is wholly untested.  The public Java API talks directly through Binder with the camera service, so only the service-side native binder interface is used today.

This binder layer is also likely to change in the future, as there's some overdue cleanup due for the camera2 API guts.  But that may not happen all that soon. But this is considered an entirely internal interface, so no guarantees about it staying as it is.

Patch Set 2:

ps2 moves the other callers of BLKGETSIZE over to using the helper function, changes the signature of the helper function so that the compiler will spot type mismatches, and adds overflow checking in the FAT case. i'm not sure whether any of the other cases need to deal with overflow? (encryption looks like it was already using a 64-bit type anyway, so i think that's fine.)

jsharkey: not sure whether you'd like to go straight to BLKGETSIZE64? this patch just fixes behavior on LP64 systems, but that patch would also let you support > 2TiB drives. (so, yeah, we should probably take this patch in the meantime because LP64 is here now whereas Android devices with that much storage are probably a little way out...)

Patch Set 1:

The point of this commit is to try to cleanup the unix_* vs. adb_* stuff so that future changes (and copy&paste code) are less likely to break Windows (which can't tolerate mismatches between the APIs).

An alternative to this would be to find a way to kill off unix_open(), unix_read(), unix_write(), unix_close() and just embed some logic in adb_open(), adb_read(), adb_write(), adb_close() to work on Windows with well-known file descriptors and C Runtime file descriptors.

I think that might be possible, but it might be too hacky. I figure that it is likely that you guys will rewrite all of this file business, so this is just a quick fix instead.

(2 comments)

Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

(3 comments)

Agreed, rotation being interrupted can cause a problem. If interrupted by a system crash, it will work just fine (logcat -L notwithstanding) since the logs in memory will in fact continue where we left off since they have effectively been wiped by the reboot. If interrupted by logcat crashing (or being requested to stop! forgot about that one), it will not overwrite, it will replay the logs (a form of stutter) rather than continuing.

One of the complications could be that logcat is stopped with a -n 99, and then restarted with -n 999. This means the rotated files will have a different namespace (eg: /data/foo.01 before, and /data/foo.001 after). The only one we can count in in both namespaces is that /data/foo will always exist.

To handle all the complications, I decided it was better to just accept that sometimes there will be this stutter, in exchange for KISS.

I will prototype an algorithm that generically searches through all the files with the same basename (regardless of the namespace), finding the latest time and see if the code looks like a maintenance issue.

To avoid going through ``foo.unrelated`` and ``foo.1-notalog`` it seems like you could just limit to the current namespace and ignore the old namespece files.

However, the previous and ad-hoc form to quickly address the complaints about the first form of the message (which was all numbers and no names) _did_ get out into preview release and thus lit a fire under me to reset the standard now to my best foot forward or hold my peace.

What is expected is that 'logcat -S' does (or will go further to) produce the tabular information associated with these expire messages in order to get a better bearing on the chatty application(s). The chatty expire messages themselves are there to help people that are triaging determine that there is missing content in the logs; and to provide some temporal data (eg: if they get a burst every 3 minutes of dropped messages, they can spot in the unexpired logs this same burst to find out what is causing the problem). So these messages are for the humans and not those that intend to parse or tabulate the data. logcat -S has more information in its hands than the chatty messages provide.

Patch Set 1:

> dear sir,
 > ran into your change by accident. don't want to suggest a differnet
 > change because I'm not in the code...sort of speak. but,
 > if you set t->sfd to be -1 although the next line can potentially
 > crash and not be ``reflected`` in the result. perhaps you should
 > check adb_close() status, or something? I'm not fully in the code.
 > hope this helps.

Thanks for the review. The code By Design sets t->sfd to -1 before calling adb_close() just in case the fd causes adb_close() to crash, in which case since t->sfd was just set, no one else in the future can try to close it again (causing problems repeatedly). So in the crash case, the code By Design leaks the fd which is preferable to leaving it around to cause more problems.

But really, this change does not have real provisions for the case of arbitrary lines of code crashing since that is a very difficult (impossible?) way to program this kind of code.

I checked the rest of the codebase and the return value of adb_close() is never checked, so this change follows that convention. adb_close() is really just an alias for unix/posix close() which is often not checked in many codebases.

I'm not the component owner, so I can't speak for them, but perhaps you can describe the simple check that you're suggesting?

I'm not sure all the details of how the AOSP handles -/+, I'd advise you to check the project documentation to guide your decision.

 > Or should we change the
 > code to check the status, document the function to return the
 > relevant error and all that? I can only suggest because I can't
 > spend too much time on the, your call!

My thinking is that larger architectural changes like this should be driven by the component owner because they're in the best position to understand their future plans for the codebase. In other words, non-component owners could prototype large changes, but it is risky if, say, the component owners are planning to do a larger rewrite or reorganization, or change to exception handling, RAII classes, etc.

Here is another example: I was thinking about cleaning up some of the logging/tracing code, but then I realized that the component owners might be rewriting all of that anyway, so any work I do (without full knowledge of their future plans) would just be wasted. So I let it be until later. Hope this helps explain where I'm coming from. Thanks.

Patch Set 8:

This linker patch depends on a mips kernel patch that is not yet at aosp, sorry.

With the revised kernel, this linker patch will correctly run all kinds of mips32 programs on mips64r6.  Without the revised kernel, this linker patch will reject running on mips64r6 any mips32 program built with old compiler defaults (-mdouble-float), whether or not that program actually uses floating point.

Without this linker patch, such mips32 programs will load, and may appear to run correctly if they have little or no use of single-precision floating point values.  If they have nontrivial uses of single-precision FP values, the mips32 program will likely suffer corrupted values.

Mips32 programs recompiled with current compiler defaults (-mfpxx) will run correctly on mips64r6, with or without the kernel patch or this linker patch.

My unit test is (N6 and N9) with my own private variant of dmesg (not strictly necessary, but we do need to compare timestamps too, which we do not anymore).

#! /bin/sh
DEVICE=``${*}``
adb ${DEVICE} logcat -b kernel -v usec -d >/tmp/3
adb ${DEVICE} shell dmesg -T >/tmp/4
sed 's/.*     0 [A-Z] //' /tmp/3 | tr -d '^M' |sed 's/^       *://' | sed 's/^\([^ ][^:]*\)  *:/\1:/' | sed 's/^  *//' >/tmp/3.1
sed 's/^[^]]*[]] //' /tmp/4 | tr -d '^M' | grep -v 'audit(' | grep -v '^ *$' >/tmp/4.1
diff -rub /tmp/[34].1 # Look for anything glaring
wc /tmp/[34].1 # should be the same number of lines.

Patch Set 1:

I was unable to reproduce the error
   Unsupported MIPS32 FloatPt ABI 6 found in ...
in my aosp repo.  That ABI 6 message would happen if debuggerd was a stale copy, ld'd from parts that included some .o piece compiled with compiler option -modd-spreg.  We now require -mno-odd-spreg in all mips32r6 modules included in mips6r6 system builds.  

I don't know how that could happen.  The -mno-odd-spreg option has been explicit in the mips32r6/mips6r6 build/core/combo/arch/mips scripts for a long time, and the current aosp mips compilers default to -mno-odd-spreg also.

Patch Set 1:

The context for why the lock is required is in logd/LogStatistics.cpp (not touched in this CL) where the helpers originate. The issue is that calls to find the pidToName and pidToUid will create entries in the table if logs have not been submitted by the pid to prefill the content. pidToName, pidToUid and uidToName all read the existing table and thus could suffer issues iterating the list if it is changing.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

or use a recursive mutex and just have the helpers lock/unlock automatically? (i'm assuming the current implementation is because you wanted callers who already hold the lock to be able to call these helpers.)

Patch Set 1:

Concerned about the risk to the others if we switch mLogElementsLock this late in the program. As it stands today, the usage is clear, and all the others that call these helpers have the lock held. I view these few holes plugged and would consider a followup cleanup with a more extensive set of unit tests?

Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

There's some extra/missing whitespace in the code formatting (see inline comments), but I also have a concern about the implementation.

It took me a little while to figure out where the initial TP-MR is assigned. The framework sets the TP-MR byte of the PDU to 0 in .gsm.SmsMessage.getSubmitPduHead(), so the RIL is responsible for filling it in. Then we get the messageRef from the response to RIL_REQUEST_SEND_SMS and this patch sets the TP-MR byte to the same value before resending.

So my only concern is that the RIL must be careful not to overwrite TP-MR with a different value when this code path is executed. Because 0-255 are all valid values for TP-MR, the correct RIL behavior is not obvious when TP-MR is zero. I suspect that at least some vendor RILs may be assigning a value to TP-MR regardless of the value passed in the PDU. 

The correct RIL behavior would probably be to assign a new TP-MR value when TP-RD is 0, and to use the value from the PDU when TP-RD is 1. Rika, is that your understanding as well, or is there something I'm missing?

The change isn't merging cleanly into our internal tree because of some variable name changes that Wink made for consistency with Android naming conventions. It's easy enough to cherry-pick into our internal tree by updating the variable names and changing Log to Rlog, but we'll have to do that by hand.

Patch Set 5:

Hi Jake, In our solution, it is actually not the RIL, but rather the WMS module in modem that looks up next TP-MR to be used from SIM @power up and supplies when TP-RD is 0.  And RIL is just a pass through.  When MO SMS failes, failed TP-MR value is propagated from WMS -> RIL -> Telephony.

What you said about ``I suspect that at least some vendor RILs may be assigning a value to TP-MR regardless of the value passed in the PDU.`` may be true, and those vendors must fix their RIL if they want this change to take effect in setting TP-RD and TP-MR correctly.

We'll fix the white spacing.

So, are you satisfied with my response or do you have any other concern?

Thanks,
Rika

Patch Set 5:

Just to be clear... So, when TP-RD is 1, TP-MR is not overwritten by WMS.  Only when TP-RD is 0, next (or new) TP-MR is assigned by WMS.

I am not sure what you meant by behavior is unknown when TP-MR is 0.  Maybe you meant when TP-RD is 0?

I don't understand the reason for this patch: CMAS messages should be handled in CdmaSMSDispatcher.dispatchMessage() by the call to sms.parseBroadcastSms() and dispatchBroadcastMessage(message), and sms.getIncomingSmsFingerprint() should only be called when the message is not a broadcast SMS.

In fact, I recently changed cdma.SmsMessage.getMessagetype() to return MESSAGE_TYPE_BROADCAST whenever the serviceCategory != 0, to work around a RIL bug that was not setting the messageType correctly for incoming CB and SMS, so the only time that getIncomingSmsFingerprint() will be called in the current code is when the service category is 0.

So I don't understand under what circumstances the service category would be non-zero where the message would not be handled by the broadcast SMS code which does not call getIncomingSmsFingerprint(). BTW, the CellBroadcastReceiver app handles detection of duplicate cell broadcasts, and they aren't detected in the framework.

Patch Set 1:

I uploaded the unit tests that I created to verify this patch.

https://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/49461/

The new unit tests require support for Shift-JIS encoding as well as decoding, which can be added to this patch in the same way that Shift-JIS decoding was added, as I mentioned in a previous comment.

Japanese characters require 2 bytes in both Shift-JIS and UTF-16, so the only benefit of Shift-JIS is that ASCII and half-width katakana characters (plus the yen symbol) are encoded in 1 byte.

In a future release, we could enable Shift-JIS encoding for messages that would benefit from it, but this will have the same problem as the Turkish (and other national language) 7-bit encodings for GSM SMS, which is that the receiving phone must support the encoding. The Turkish 7-bit tables are only enabled for encoding on Turkish SIM cards by default (or they can be enabled for a specific device build using a config property), to comply with Turkish law requiring their use. All devices can decode messages encoded with any of the national language tables, but they are only used for encoding when specifically enabled by a custom build property or the detection of a Turkish SIM card.

So the reasons that I think this patch should add an else branch to BearerData.encodeUserDataPayload() to support encoding with Shift-JIS when a UserData object is passed which specifically requests it are for symmetry and because it makes it easier to write test cases such as the ones I just uploaded. However, we shouldn't make any other code changes to enable the use of Shift-JIS for the normal code paths.

In the future, if a Japanese CDMA carrier specifically requests Shift-JIS to be enabled for encoding, we can add code to enable it under specific conditions (e.g. registered network has Japanese MCC or device has Shift-JIS encoding enabled via build property), as we did for the Turkish case.

Patch Set 1:

If you try to install a forward-locked app (proprietary app), it creates an ext4 image for the app storage that is then mounted under /mnt/asec, and it ends up unlabeled.  Shows up if you do an adb install -l on the apk file, but
should also show up if you install a proprietary app from the market.  Proposing some modifications to vold to support fixing this situation.  The other option would be to change
vold to pass a context= mount option when mounting the image
under /mnt/asec, in which case all files within it would be treated as having a single security context versus the much more granular approach I'm offering. Thought I would open up the discussion on this topic with the patchset. Regardless of the approach taken, the unlabeled files need to be fixed.

This patch does depend on some ext4 changes though (I9bdc8659aae7037ccebbf4464500b79b4b2f56af) since I'm not passing a file_context option around.

Patch Set 4:

Hi Wink

For cdma, currently supported ID range is 0x1000 to 0x1004. I see your concern in RIL.java if range is increased in future. However, because currently supported IDs are limited, this would be a good start to enable OEM for cdma CMAS support.

See my change in https://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/46887/

manager.enableCellBroadcastRange(
SmsEnvelope.SERVICE_CATEGORY_CMAS_PRESIDENTIAL_LEVEL_ALERT, //0x1000
SmsEnvelope.SERVICE_CATEGORY_CMAS_TEST_MESSAGE); //0x1004

Also, we have been supporting OEM with CDMA CMAS for a while..since gingerbread days.  Changes were uploaded to codeaurora site, but only recently we uploaded to aosp.  Jake added Cdma CMAS support from JB, but enable/disable APIs were still not supported.

Rika

Patch Set 1:

Why can the user not modify mvno data?  For carriers without MVNO the user can modify everything to configure the connection.  Why is MVNO data special?

Patch Set 1:

Dear Roberts

 Basically MVNO key is based on carrier's policy and write it down in USIM. and then we should compare the key value in user's USIM with that of APN data. Because of that, new logic would automatically insert ``saved`` MVNO key,that saved when USIM loaded. If user added new APN with wrong MVNO data, it does not work and cannot show no more in APN list.
 And new logic is also implemented if does not exist matched MVNO key, it would list up major carrier's APNs with MCC/MNC ,without MVNO.

Patch Set 1:

The current APN code is written so that the user can fix the data and regain a connection to their carrier if the carrier changes configurations.  I do not think the MVNO data should be different in this regard - if the user incorrectly enters or changes the apn db they have the potential to break their connections, but also they have the ability to fix it.

Patch Set 1:

Are there mvno cases where we need spn, imsi-mask and gid data, or even 2 of the 3?  Or is the situation such that the mvno_type field dictates what 1 piece of data we need to determine an mvno match?

I'm inclined to use mvno_type and mvno_match_data fields.

Patch Set 1: -Code-Review Verified+1

Have confirmed functional with init setprop permissions enabled, selinux adjustments, and AID_SYSTEM enabled to set logcat -G runtime values. All this code is good, except we must limit the set to 64K - 4M (which takes 20Mb of memory for all four logs), anything larger is to be viewed as a DOS attack.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Added (back) the 16MB setting because in the logd+init review we declared 3% individual memory impact as our maximum, and would allow 16MB on a svelte device as a result.

NB: we do not pre-allocate the buffer, this is an impact only felt over a long period of time, and only if the logs in all 5 categories filled up to the brim.

Patch Set 1:

Haojun, thanks for the submission.  Is there a test case that shows this problem?  Please note that MediaPlayer::decode is calling MediaPlayerService::decode through Binder.

Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

> Haojun, thanks for the submission.  Is there a test case that shows
 > this problem?  Please note that MediaPlayer::decode is calling
 > MediaPlayerService::decode through Binder.

Andy, thank you for your reply. No, I don't have a test case, but I do have a use case. In our company's source code, there is a use case where MediaPlayer::decode is calling MediaPlayerService::decode directly, not through a binder. (They are in the same process, for the reason of performance, somebody in our company decided to do SoundPool effect in the media server, but I'm not sure, really.)

But a binder should just be an implementation detail, right? The point of RPC is to make it like a local procedure call, now when we call it locally, we found we are closing the fd twice...

Sorry for my ill English, please feel free to contact me. Also see my inline comments.
